        excerpt: `Understanding the role of natural light in shaping spatial perception and emotional response in residential design.`,
        tags: ['residential', 'nature'],
        content: 'Architecture is often defined by its physical boundaries—walls, floors, ceilings. Yet, it is the intangible element of light that breathes life into these static forms. At Arcadia, we treat light not merely as a utility for visibility, but as a primary building material, as tangible and manipulable as concrete or timber. It carves volume, defines depth, and dictates the rhythm of a space throughout the day.\n\nThe Ephemeral Sculptor\n\nWhen we approach a new project, particularly in residential design, our solar studies begin before the first sketch is drawn. We map the heliodon, understanding exactly how the sun will traverse the site at the winter solstice versus the summer peak. This data informs the orientation of glazing, the depth of overhangs, and the placement of light wells.\n\nBy manipulating aperture sizes and positions, we can curate the user\'s experience of time. A morning breakfast nook might be flooded with the crisp, blue-toned light of the east, awakening the senses. Conversely, a living area designed for evening relaxation captures the warm, horizontal rays of the setting sun, casting long shadows that emphasize texture and warmth.'
