        excerpt: `Strategies for minimizing waste by designing for disassembly and reusing structural components.`,
        tags: ['sustainability', 'materials'],
        content: 'Designing for Disassembly\n\nThe construction industry is one of the world\'s largest consumers of raw materials. To mitigate this impact, we must fundamentally shift how we conceive of buildings—not as permanent monuments, but as material banks for the future.\n\nThe concept of the circular economy in architecture revolves around the principle of closing resource loops. Instead of the traditional linear model—extraction, production, usage, and disposal—we advocate for a system where materials are kept in use for as long as possible, extracting the maximum value from them whilst in use, then recovering and regenerating products and materials at the end of each service life.\n\nAt Arcadia Studio, we are pioneering "Design for Disassembly" (DfD). This methodology ensures that building components can be easily deconstructed and reused without losing value. By using mechanical fixings instead of chemical adhesives, and standardizing components, we transform buildings into depots of valuable resources ready for their next life cycle.\n\n"We need to stop looking at demolition as the end of a building\'s life, and start viewing it as the harvest of materials for the next generation of architecture."'
